      T+1
   =20
 =20

There are in principle two ways to buy a thing:
=09You reach an agreement with a seller to buy the thing, then you go off t=
o get your money and the seller goes off to get the thing, then you meet ba=
ck somewhere and exchange the money for the thing.=09You come to the seller=
 with money, and she=E2=80=99s got the thing sitting right there, and you a=
gree on the trade by doing it: You hand her the money, she hands you the th=
ing, there is no additional step.

The second approach is pretty familiar from, like, going to the store and b=
uying stuff.
  [3]
 But most of finance works the other way. Imagine buying a house the second=
 way. You=E2=80=99d have to go around to open houses with a gigantic sack o=
f cash, so that when you saw a house you liked you could say to the seller =
=E2=80=9CI want it=E2=80=9D and hand her the sack. But if you saw a house y=
ou=C2=A0didn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0like =E2=80=94=C2=A0or if you saw one you did l=
ike but your offer got rejected =E2=80=94=C2=A0you=E2=80=99d just have to d=
rag the sack back out with you. Very inconvenient! Also where would you get=
 the sack of cash from? No bank would lend you a giant sack of cash just to=
 drag around with you in case you found a house to buy. In our actual world=
, the way it works is that you put down an offer on a house, and it=E2=80=
=99s accepted, and then you go to a bank and say =E2=80=9Cwould you lend me=
 money secured by this house,=E2=80=9D and the bank says =E2=80=9Csure,=E2=
=80=9D and then there is a closing where you get the house and the bank get=
s a lien on the house and the seller gets the cash all at exactly the same =
time.
Similarly with mergers and acquisitions. When Elon Musk wanted to buy Twitt=
er Inc., he did not have $44=C2=A0billion in his checking account, and Twit=
ter did not expect him to. The order of operations is that he offered a pri=
ce, Twitter=E2=80=99s board said =E2=80=9Chmm but will you have the money,=
=E2=80=9D he provided evidence that he would have the money, Twitter=E2=80=
=99s board accepted his offer, he rounded up the actual money (some of it f=
rom bank loans secured by Twitter), and then he gave the money to Twitter=
=E2=80=99s shareholders and they gave him shares.
  [4]
=C2=A0And that=E2=80=99s how most mergers work; it would be weird for any b=
uyer to pre-fund an acquisition.
But this is also how normal=C2=A0stock trades work. The normal way to do a =
stock trade, for institutional investors, is:
=09You put in an order on the stock exchange to buy a stock.=09The order ge=
ts filled: Someone agrees to sell you the stock.=09You go get the money, th=
ey go get the stock, and you meet back up in two days to exchange them.

This is not necessarily everyone=E2=80=99s experience of=C2=A0retail=C2=A0s=
tock trading (many brokers will make you pre-fund your trades), but it is a=
n important lubrication for the financial system. Some orders don=E2=80=99t=
 get filled; some investors buy opportunistically on different venues at di=
fferent times. If you needed to park $100 million on the stock exchange to =
be able to buy $100 million worth of stock, it would make things inefficien=
t: There are a lot of stock exchanges, some of which sometimes have better =
prices, and you could only trade on the exchange where you have parked mone=
y. You might want to buy more stock if prices drop, but you can=E2=80=99t i=
f you don=E2=80=99t have money parked on the exchange yet; you might want t=
o buy less stock if prices go up, and then your money is inefficiently park=
ed at the exchange doing nothing. It=E2=80=99s more efficient to have just-=
in-time manufacturing for stock trades, where you do the trade and then com=
e up with the money. You don=E2=80=99t need the cash to do the trade; you j=
ust need people to believe that, when the trade settles, you=E2=80=99ll hav=
e the money.
On the other hand just-in-time manufacturing is always more fragile than ke=
eping a lot of inventory around, and sometimes this system leads to trouble=
. One sort of trouble it could lead to is: You agree to buy a lot of stock,=
 then you can=E2=80=99t come up with the money.=C2=A0In practice the stock =
market has a system of clearinghouses where traders and their brokers post =
collateral to guarantee their trades, and that mostly tends to work. (  Not=
 all the time in every market.)
But another sort of trouble it can lead to is   what happened to GameStop C=
orp. stock in January 2021: Robinhood Markets Inc. had so many customers bu=
ying so much of a handful of volatile meme stocks that the clearinghouse ca=
lled it demanding more collateral; it didn=E2=80=99t have the money, so it =
shut down purchases of those meme stocks, leaving customers furious and lit=
igious. If US stock settlement was faster, it would involve less credit ris=
k, so it would require less (and less volatile) collateral, so stuff like t=
hat probably wouldn=E2=80=99t happen.
  [5]

And so,   in part in response to the meme-stock episode,=C2=A0the US stock =
market is   moving from T+2 settlement to T+1 settlement, where you trade s=
tock on a=C2=A0Monday and settle (exchange dollars for stock) on a Tuesday.=
 There was, and still is, a lot of wishful talk about instantaneous or same=
-day settlement, but that might run into difficulties with investors who ne=
ed time to line up their funding. But T+1 seems fine; it still gives you a =
day to find the money to buy the stock. You hit =E2=80=9Cbuy,=E2=80=9D your=
 order gets filled, you wire some money from your bank account to your brok=
erage, you buy the stock, it=E2=80=99s fine.
Unless your money is not in dollars. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Greg Ritchie repor=
ted this week:

At major financial institutions including banks, brokers and investment hou=
ses, currency desks are preparing for the world=E2=80=99s biggest stock mar=
ket to halve the time it takes to settle equity transactions to just one da=
y.
That switch =E2=80=94 due in May next year =E2=80=94 will put US stocks out=
 of step with the world of foreign exchange, where trades typically take tw=
o days to complete. It means many overseas institutions trying to buy Ameri=
can assets will need to secure dollars in advance to ensure they can make s=
ettlement =E2=80=94 or face a desperate scramble to find the cash in time. =
...
=E2=80=9CFor international participants wanting to buy US securities, pre-f=
unding the transaction with US dollars or arranging for a short-dated T+1 F=
X settlement will be required,=E2=80=9D said Joe Urban, managing director o=
f electronic trading at Clear Street. =E2=80=9CAny pre-funding requirement =
could potentially push asset managers out of the market for one day, driven=
 by the need to raise US dollars a day prior for today=E2=80=99s transactio=
n.=E2=80=9D

Today, if you are a big asset manager and you want to buy stocks, you press=
 the =E2=80=9Cbuy=E2=80=9D button and then worry about the mechanics.=C2=A0=
After T+1 settlement starts, for some big international asset managers, fir=
st you will have to spend a day getting your money set up before you can hi=
t the =E2=80=9Cbuy=E2=80=9D button. Probably you=E2=80=99ll miss a few trad=
es while you=E2=80=99re waiting. Or you=E2=80=99ll find a way to get the mo=
ney set up faster:

More than half of European firms with fewer than 10,000 staff are planning =
to either move people to North America or hire overnight staff in Europe or=
 Asia, according to a survey sponsored by the Depository Trust and Clearing=
 Corporation. =E2=80=A6
In its letter to the SEC, Baillie Gifford said US FX desks typically close =
early on Friday evenings, which might mean trades need to be made in Asian =
hours on a T+0 basis. It suggested US regulators encourage banks to extend =
their trading activities to at least 6 p.m., five days a week.
=E2=80=9CWho is going to be there at the end of the day at 5pm on a Friday =
to give us a price?=E2=80=9D Baillie Gifford=E2=80=99s Lawlor said.


