      Odey
   =20
 =20

If you have been accused of something terrible, your first reaction might b=
e to call a lawyer. You will speak candidly to the lawyer about your situat=
ion, and she will discuss it with you, and then either she will be your law=
yer or she won=E2=80=99t. If she becomes your lawyer =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you =
want to hire her and she agrees to work for you =E2=80=94=C2=A0then she wil=
l have a professional obligation to keep your secrets and not gossip about =
you to the press. If she does=C2=A0not=C2=A0become your lawyer =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0if you decide not to hire her, or if you offer to but she turns you down=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0she will=C2=A0also=C2=A0have a professional obligation to k=
eep the secrets that you told her in your initial consultation.
  [6]

If you have been accused of a certain sort of terrible thing, and you are a=
 certain sort of person, your second reaction might be to call a corporate =
intelligence firm to dig up dirt on your accusers. You will speak candidly =
to the corporate intelligence guy, and he will discuss the case with you, a=
nd then either he will be your dirt-digger or he won=E2=80=99t. I do not kn=
ow the ethical rules that apply to corporate intelligence firms! But appare=
ntly, when they end up not taking=C2=A0a case, they are   happy to talk to =
the press about it:

Crispin Odey approached a private investigator who had done work for disgra=
ced movie producer Harvey Weinstein to discuss the =E2=80=9Cmassive witch h=
unt=E2=80=9D he faced after fresh claims of sexual misconduct.
=E2=80=9CHarvey had access to a lot of so much more attractive girls, I hav=
e to tell you,=E2=80=9D Odey joked during the 17-minute phone call. =E2=80=
=9CIf you lose an arm, you only get ten grand =E2=80=94 you know, if someon=
e touches you on the bottom you might be able to get a hundred grand,=E2=80=
=9D he said elsewhere in the call.
The financier was speaking in late June to Seth Freedman, who runs London-b=
ased corporate intelligence firm Red Mist. The pair ultimately didn=E2=80=
=99t work together, and Freedman shared his recording of the call with Bloo=
mberg News, saying it was important that the public hears Odey=E2=80=99s th=
inking about the situation at the time.

Okay! What is your model of Freedman=E2=80=99s thinking here? Like, I feel =
like if you run a corporate intelligence firm, a=C2=A0certain amount=C2=A0o=
f your business is going to come from people who, uh, are not afraid to say=
 and also possibly do some monstrous stuff. (Freedman worked for Harvey Wei=
nstein!) If you record them saying monstrous stuff and release the juiciest=
 stuff to the press, won=E2=80=99t you lose a lot of business? Future lucra=
tive monsters, reasonably, won=E2=80=99t trust you.
I suppose you could consciously choose that approach to distinguish yoursel=
f as, like, a Good corporate intelligence firm, one that vets its clients a=
nd only works for good innocent upstanding ones who do not say monstrous th=
ings in their initial consultations. (But, again: Weinstein!) Ostentatiousl=
y turning down (and turning on) some clients might make you more attractive=
 to others.
Or, also, I mean, I don=E2=80=99t know=C2=A0why=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthe pair ulti=
mately didn=E2=80=99t work together,=E2=80=9D and I suppose an approach lik=
e =E2=80=9Cif you don=E2=80=99t hire me I will leak your secrets to the pre=
ss=E2=80=9D has some advantages. Also it does demonstrate the ruthlessness =
that one wants in a corporate intelligence investigator.

