<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are in principle two ways to buy a thing=
:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You reach an agreement with a seller =
to buy the thing, then you go off to get your money and the seller goes off=
 to get the thing, then you meet back somewhere and exchange the money for =
the thing.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You come to the seller =
with money, and she=E2=80=99s got the thing sitting right there, and you ag=
ree on the trade by doing it: You hand her the money, she hands you the thi=
ng, there is no additional step.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The second approach is pretty familiar from, l=
ike, going to the store and buying stuff.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> But most of finance works the other way. Imagine buying a house the se=
cond way. You=E2=80=99d have to go around to open houses with a gigantic sa=
ck of cash, so that when you saw a house you liked you could say to the sel=
ler =E2=80=9CI want it=E2=80=9D and hand her the sack. But if you saw a hou=
se you=C2=A0<em>didn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>like =E2=80=94=C2=A0or if you saw =
one you did like but your offer got rejected =E2=80=94=C2=A0you=E2=80=99d j=
ust have to drag the sack back out with you. Very inconvenient! Also where =
would you get the sack of cash from? No bank would lend you a giant sack of=
 cash just to drag around with you in case you found a house to buy. In our=
 actual world, the way it works is that you put down an offer on a house, a=
nd it=E2=80=99s accepted, and then you go to a bank and say =E2=80=9Cwould =
you lend me money secured by this house,=E2=80=9D and the bank says =E2=80=
=9Csure,=E2=80=9D and then there is a closing where you get the house and t=
he bank gets a lien on the house and the seller gets the cash all at exactl=
y the same time.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Similarly with mergers and acquisitions. When =
Elon Musk wanted to buy Twitter Inc., he did not have $44=C2=A0billion in h=
is checking account, and Twitter did not expect him to. The order of operat=
ions is that he offered a price, Twitter=E2=80=99s board said =E2=80=9Chmm =
but will you have the money,=E2=80=9D he <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/32862759.260423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9v=
cGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtMjEvZWxvbi1nb3QtaGlzLW1vbmV5P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA=
5MjgyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJn=
V0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDkyOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cBfc8bf286" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">provided evidence that he would have the money</a>, Tw=
itter=E2=80=99s board accepted his offer, he rounded up the actual money (s=
ome of it from bank loans secured by Twitter), and then he gave the money t=
o Twitter=E2=80=99s shareholders and they gave him shares.<a class=3D"footn=
ote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: n=
one !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bor=
der-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important=
; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0And that=E2=80=99s how most mergers work; it would be weird for a=
ny buyer to pre-fund an acquisition.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But this is also how <em>normal=C2=A0</em>stoc=
k trades work. The normal way to do a stock trade, for institutional invest=
ors, is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You put in an order on the stock exch=
ange to buy a stock.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The order get=
s filled: Someone agrees to sell you the stock.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">You go get the money, they go get the stock, and you meet bac=
k up in two days to exchange them.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is not necessarily everyone=E2=80=99s exp=
erience of=C2=A0<em>retail=C2=A0</em>stock trading (many brokers will make =
you pre-fund your trades), but it is an important lubrication for the finan=
cial system. Some orders don=E2=80=99t get filled; some investors buy oppor=
tunistically on different venues at different times. If you needed to park =
$100 million on the stock exchange to be able to buy $100 million worth of =
stock, it would make things inefficient: There are a lot of stock exchanges=
, some of which sometimes have better prices, and you could only trade on t=
he exchange where you have parked money. You might want to buy more stock i=
f prices drop, but you can=E2=80=99t if you don=E2=80=99t have money parked=
 on the exchange yet; you might want to buy less stock if prices go up, and=
 then your money is inefficiently parked at the exchange doing nothing. It=
=E2=80=99s more efficient to have just-in-time manufacturing for stock trad=
es, where you do the trade and then come up with the money. You don=E2=80=
=99t need the cash to do the trade; you just need people to believe that, w=
hen the trade settles, you=E2=80=99ll have the money.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand just-in-time manufacturing i=
s always more fragile than keeping a lot of inventory around, and sometimes=
 this system leads to trouble. One sort of trouble it could lead to is: You=
 agree to buy a lot of stock, then you can=E2=80=99t come up with the money=
.=C2=A0In practice the stock market has a system of clearinghouses where tr=
aders and their brokers post collateral to guarantee their trades, and that=
 mostly tends to work. (<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/32862759.260423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljb=
GVzLzIwMjItMDctMDcvbmlja2VsLWJpZy1zaG90LWNhbGxlZC10aGUtc2hvdHM_Y21waWQ9QkJE=
MDkyODIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXI=
mdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwOTI4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cB1326b759" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">  Not all the time</a> in every market.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But another sort of trouble it can lead to is =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32862759.260423/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDEtMjkvcmVkZ=
Gl0LXRyYWRlcnMtb24tcm9iaW5ob29kLWFyZS1vbi1ib3RoLXNpZGVzLW9mLWdhbWVzdG9wP2Nt=
cGlkPUJCRDA5MjgyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXd=
zbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDkyOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cB9059736e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">  what happened to GameStop Corp. stock in =
January 2021</a>: Robinhood Markets Inc. had so many customers buying so mu=
ch of a handful of volatile meme stocks that the clearinghouse called it de=
manding more collateral; it didn=E2=80=99t have the money, so it shut down =
purchases of those meme stocks, leaving customers furious and litigious. If=
 US stock settlement was faster, it would involve less credit risk, so it w=
ould require less (and less volatile) collateral, so stuff like that probab=
ly wouldn=E2=80=99t happen.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importa=
nt; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/32862759.260423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlu=
aW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMTkvbWF0dC1sZXZpbmUtcy1tb25leS1zdHVmZi1nYW1lc3R=
vcC1iYWZmbGVzLXRoZS1zZWMtdG9vP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA5MjgyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZW=
RpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDkyOCZ1dG1fY2Ftc=
GFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB15373fce" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  in part =
in response</a> to the meme-stock episode,=C2=A0the US stock market is <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32862759.260423/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDItMTAvcHJpdmF0Z=
S1mdW5kcy1hcmUtdGhlLW5ldy1wdWJsaWMtZnVuZHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDkyODIzX01PTkVZU1RV=
RkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwOTI=
4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1a719849" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
">  moving from T+2 settlement to T+1 settlement</a>, where you trade stock=
 on a=C2=A0Monday and settle (exchange dollars for stock) on a Tuesday. The=
re was, and still is, a lot of wishful talk about instantaneous or same-day=
 settlement, but that might run into difficulties with investors who need t=
ime to line up their funding. But T+1 seems fine; it still gives you a day =
to find the money to buy the stock. You hit =E2=80=9Cbuy,=E2=80=9D your ord=
er gets filled, you wire some money from your bank account to your brokerag=
e, you buy the stock, it=E2=80=99s fine.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Unless your money is not in dollars. Bloomberg=
=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3286275=
9.260423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDktMj=
Yvd2FsbC1zdHJlZXQtcy1uZWVkLWZvci1zcGVlZC1pbi1zdG9ja3MtaXMtcmVzaGFwaW5nLXRoZ=
S1meC13b3JsZD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwOTI4MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0=
bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA5MjgmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R=
1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB847c8b65" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Greg Ritchie reported this =
week</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At major financial institutions including bank=
s, brokers and investment houses, currency desks are preparing for the worl=
d=E2=80=99s biggest stock market to halve the time it takes to settle equit=
y transactions to just one day.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That switch =E2=80=94 due in May next year =E2=
=80=94 will put US stocks out of step with the world of foreign exchange, w=
here trades typically take two days to complete. It means many overseas ins=
titutions trying to buy American assets will need to secure dollars in adva=
nce to ensure they can make settlement =E2=80=94 or face a desperate scramb=
le to find the cash in time. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CFor international participants wantin=
g to buy US securities, pre-funding the transaction with US dollars or arra=
nging for a short-dated T+1 FX settlement will be required,=E2=80=9D said J=
oe Urban, managing director of electronic trading at Clear Street. =E2=80=
=9CAny pre-funding requirement could potentially push asset managers out of=
 the market for one day, driven by the need to raise US dollars a day prior=
 for today=E2=80=99s transaction.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Today, if you are a big asset manager and you =
want to buy stocks, you press the =E2=80=9Cbuy=E2=80=9D button and then wor=
ry about the mechanics.=C2=A0After T+1 settlement starts, for some big inte=
rnational asset managers, first you will have to spend a day getting your m=
oney set up before you can hit the =E2=80=9Cbuy=E2=80=9D button. Probably y=
ou=E2=80=99ll miss a few trades while you=E2=80=99re waiting. Or you=E2=80=
=99ll find a way to get the money set up faster:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">More than half of European firms with fewer th=
an 10,000 staff are planning to either move people to North America or hire=
 overnight staff in Europe or Asia, according to a survey sponsored by the =
Depository Trust and Clearing Corporation. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In its letter to the SEC, Baillie Gifford said=
 US FX desks typically close early on Friday evenings, which might mean tra=
des need to be made in Asian hours on a T+0 basis. It suggested US regulato=
rs encourage banks to extend their trading activities to at least 6 p.m., f=
ive days a week.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWho is going to be there at the end o=
f the day at 5pm on a Friday to give us a price?=E2=80=9D Baillie Gifford=
=E2=80=99s Lawlor said.</p>
</blockquote>
